         <abstract id="aspace_943c044f8732a18a87af10c8fe856413">The collection includes 34 charcoal set design sketches by Albert M. Pyke of scenes from the film Mourning Becomes Electra, produced and directed by Dudley Nichols. The drawings, dating from circa 1947, are on mountings measuring 35 3/4" x 29 3/4" and smaller. Each drawing has a title label which reads: "Dudley Nichols Production of Eugene O'Neill's Mourning Becomes Electra [title of drawing] William E. Flannery, Art Director."</abstract>
         <origination label="creator">
            <persname identifier="http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/no2014126043"
                      source="naf">
               <part>Pyke, Albert M., 1897-1978</part>
            </persname>
         </origination>
         <origination label="creator">
            <persname identifier="http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n2017053465"
                      source="naf">
               <part>O'Neill, Eugene, 1888-1953. ( Mourning becomes Electra)</part>
            </persname>
         </origination>
    
      </did>
      <acqinfo id="aspace_46bf03f0c0d071e35999d440adb8bb6b">
         <head>Immediate Source of Acquisition</head>
         <p>Gift of Dudley Nichols, 1947.</p>  
      </acqinfo>
      <accessrestrict id="aspace_769af75292f721524291357729fd99a5">
         <head>Conditions Governing Access</head>
         <p>The materials are open for research.</p>  
      </accessrestrict>
      <processinfo id="aspace_ff352da16ee1b0a5225ee7df3f81361b">
         <head>Processing Information</head>
         <p>Collections are processed to a variety of levels, depending on the work necessary to make them usable, their perceived research value, the availability of staff, competing priorities, and whether or not further accruals are expected. The library attempts to provide a basic level of preservation and access for all collections and does more extensive processing of higher priority collections as time and resources permit.</p>
         <p>This collection received a basic level of processing, including rehousing and minimal organization, in 2013. The titles in the listing were transcribed from the drawings.</p>
         <p>This finding aid may be updated periodically to account for new acquisitions to the collection and/or revisions in arrangement and description.</p>
         <p>The collection is comprised of material formerly classed as ZA Theatre Guild.</p>  
      </processinfo>
      <bioghist id="aspace_72a41a8c485022eae52ea5edc208d926">
         <head>Albert M. Pyke (1897-1978)</head>
         <p>Albert M. Pyke was an American film and television set designer and art director.</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_2c5321460acf8e8a24305692af35e5bd">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The collection includes 34 charcoal set design sketches by Albert M. Pyke of scenes from the film Mourning Becomes Electra, produced and directed by Dudley Nichols. The drawings, dating from circa 1947, are on mountings measuring 35 3/4" x 29 3/4" and smaller. Each drawing has a title label which reads: "Dudley Nichols Production of Eugene O'Neill's <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
               <part>Mourning Becomes Electra</part>
            </title> [title of drawing] William E. Flannery, Art Director.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <arrangement id="aspace_2d3d976b47273eb7d3a1c97ccb024bb1">
         <head>Arrangement</head>
         <p>The drawings are arranged in the order in which they were initially inventoried by the library.</p>  
      </arrangement>
